// Semantic direction:
// authn verifies that a request comes from a claimed identity.
// authorization_code_flow is the secure OAuth2 flow for web applications.
// pkce (Proof Key for Code Exchange) adds a code_verifier/code_challenge pair to prevent code interception.
// auth_state is a random value sent in auth_request and verified on return to prevent CSRF.
// token_request exchanges auth_code for access_token and id_token.
// access_token authorizes API calls; it is short-lived and scoped.
// refresh_token is long-lived and exchanges for new access_tokens without re-authentication.
// id_token is a signed JWT carrying user identity claims (subject, email, name).
// oidc_provider publishes its public keys at jwks_uri; discovery_url lists all endpoints.
// id_token_verify validates the signature against jwks, checks audience_check and nonce_oidc.
// jwk_kid identifies which key in the JWKS was used to sign the token.
// token_introspect queries the authorization server to check if an opaque token is still active.
// session_id is a cryptographically random identifier stored in a cookie.
// session_rotate_id creates a new session_id after privilege escalation to prevent fixation.
// sliding_expiry resets the session_expires on each access; absolute_expiry is a hard limit.
// csrf_token is a per-session secret included in state-changing forms.
// double_submit_cookie stores the CSRF token in both a cookie and a request parameter.
// same_site_strict prevents the session cookie from being sent on cross-site requests.
// totp generates time-based one-time passwords from a shared totp_secret (RFC 6238).
// totp_window allows ±1 time step to account for clock skew.
// webauthn is the W3C standard for phishing-resistant hardware key authentication.
// webauthn_challenge is a server-generated random value signed by the authenticator.
// recovery_code is a pre-generated single-use backup for MFA device loss.

// Primitive flow:
// login: redirect to oidc_provider with auth_request (state, nonce, pkce challenge)
// callback: verify state + code_verifier -> token_request -> id_token + access_token
//   -> id_token_verify: jwks lookup by kid -> signature + aud + nonce check
//   -> session_create(user_id, claims) -> session_id cookie (HttpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Lax)
// API request: session_id cookie -> session_get -> session_user
//   sliding_expiry: session_update(expires = now + ttl)
// CSRF: form submission -> csrf_validate(token from form == token in session)
// MFA: post-password -> mfa_required -> totp_verify(code, secret, window)
//   or: webauthn_challenge -> authenticator signs -> webauthn_authenticate

// This defines OAuth2/OIDC authentication flows, PKCE, session management,
// CSRF protection, TOTP, and WebAuthn multi-factor authentication.

