// Semantic direction:
// socket is the fundamental I/O handle for network communication.
// socket_create allocates a socket with the given family, type, and protocol.
// socket_bind attaches the socket to a local socket_addr; required for servers.
// socket_listen marks the socket as passive and sets the connection backlog.
// socket_accept waits for an incoming connection and returns a new socket_fd for it.
// socket_connect initiates a connection to a remote socket_addr.
// tcp_nodelay disables Nagle's algorithm, reducing latency for small writes.
// tcp_keepalive detects dead connections by sending probes after keepalive_idle silence.
// so_reuseaddr allows binding to a recently-used port without waiting for TIME_WAIT.
// so_reuseport allows multiple sockets to bind the same port for load-balanced accept.
// udp_send_to sends a datagram to an explicit address; udp_recv_from captures the sender's address.
// udp_multicast_join subscribes to a multicast_group for one-to-many UDP delivery.
// async_io uses the OS event notification mechanism (io_uring on Linux, kqueue on macOS).
// io_uring submits I/O operations as a batch via a submission ring and collects completions.
// epoll registers fds of interest; wait_events blocks until any registered fd is event_readable or event_writable.
// non_blocking sets a socket so reads/writes return would_block instead of blocking.
// io_pending marks an operation that should be retried when the fd becomes ready.
// socket_pool recycles connected sockets to avoid the overhead of repeated connect/close.
// unix_domain sockets provide IPC on the same machine with lower overhead than TCP.

// Primitive flow:
// TCP server: socket_create(ipv4, stream) -> socket_bind(addr) -> socket_listen
//   -> loop: socket_accept -> spawn handler(fd) -> tcp_read/write -> socket_close
// TCP client: socket_create -> set_nonblocking -> socket_connect (non-blocking)
//   -> epoll: wait event_writable -> connection complete -> tcp_read/write
// async read: register_fd(fd, event_readable) -> wait_events -> tcp_read
//   -> would_block: re-register -> wait again
// UDP server: socket_create(ipv4, dgram) -> socket_bind -> loop: udp_recv_from -> process -> udp_send_to

// This defines TCP/UDP socket primitives, async I/O via epoll/kqueue/io_uring,
// non-blocking operation, socket pools, and Unix domain sockets.

