// Semantic direction:
// dns_resolver sends queries to nameservers and caches responses.
// resolver_config reads from /etc/resolv.conf: nameservers, search_domains, ndots.
// ndots controls when a name is treated as absolute vs. searched with search_domains appended.
// rotate_nameservers cycles through nameservers instead of always trying the first.
// dns_query asks for records of query_type for query_name in class_in (Internet).
// recursion_desired asks the nameserver to resolve the full chain on the client's behalf.
// dns_message is the wire-format structure: fixed header with message_flags plus four sections.
// flag_qr is 0 for query, 1 for response; flag_aa means the answering server is authoritative.
// flag_tc means the message was truncated; the client should retry over TCP.
// rcode_nxdomain means the domain does not exist; rcode_servfail means the nameserver had an error.
// a_record maps a hostname to an IPv4 address; aaaa_record maps to an IPv6 address.
// cname_record is an alias; the resolver follows the chain until an A or AAAA record is reached.
// mx_record names a mail server with a priority (lower = preferred).
// srv_record names a service endpoint with priority, weight, port, and target hostname.
// txt_record carries arbitrary text strings, used for DKIM, SPF, domain verification.
// cache_negative stores nxdomain results for negative_ttl to avoid repeated failed lookups.
// resolve_srv enables service discovery: resolve_srv("_http._tcp.example.com") → [(host, port)].
// reverse_lookup converts an IP address to a hostname using PTR records.
// hosts_file is checked before DNS; entries map names to IPs without a network round-trip.
// mdns (Multicast DNS) resolves .local names on the local network without a central server.

// Primitive flow:
// resolve_host("example.com"):
//   hosts_lookup -> hit: return IP
//   dns_cache lookup -> cache_hit: return record
//   build dns_query(name, A, IN) -> send to nameserver_addr:53 (UDP)
//   -> dns_response parse -> answer_section
//   -> cname_record? -> follow chain -> A record
//   -> cache_store(name, IP, record_ttl)
//   -> return ipv4_addr
// SRV discovery: resolve_srv("_grpc._tcp.service.internal")
//   -> srv_records sorted by priority then weighted random by weight
//   -> [(host, port)] list for connection
// TCP retry: flag_tc set -> re-send query over TCP port 53

// This defines DNS query construction, wire-format parsing, recursive resolution,
// caching with negative TTL, SRV service discovery, reverse lookups, and mDNS.

