// Semantic direction:
// proxy_forward routes client requests to external servers on the client's behalf.
// proxy_reverse receives requests from the internet and forwards to internal backends.
// proxy_transparent intercepts traffic without client configuration via NAT rules.
// http_connect_tunnel is the HTTP method for establishing a TCP tunnel through a proxy.
// connect_target is the host:port the client wants to reach; the proxy relays bytes between client and target.
// relay_bidirectional copies bytes in both directions simultaneously until either end closes.
// socks5 is a general-purpose proxy protocol supporting TCP connect, UDP, and domain name resolution.
// socks5_handshake negotiates the auth method: no_auth or username/password.
// socks5_connect asks the server to open a TCP connection to socks5_addr.
// socks5_udp_associate sets up a UDP relay channel; datagrams are wrapped with address headers.
// socks5_domain sends the hostname to the proxy for resolution, enabling remote DNS lookup.
// socks4a_domain is the SOCKS4 extension for domain names; socks4 only supports IPv4.
// reverse_proxy selects an upstream backend using backend_select (round-robin, hash, least-conn).
// sticky_session routes requests from the same client to the same backend using a session_cookie.
// proxy_rewrite_url modifies the request path before forwarding (strip prefix, add prefix).
// x_forwarded_for appends the client IP to the header chain for logging and access control.
// x_forwarded_proto tells the backend whether the original request used HTTP or HTTPS.
// ssl_termination decrypts TLS at the proxy and forwards plain HTTP to the backend.
// ssl_passthrough forwards encrypted bytes without decrypting (backend handles TLS).
// tunnel_wireguard provides an encrypted layer-3 tunnel; tunnel_allowed_ips filters routed CIDRs.

// Primitive flow:
// forward proxy (HTTP CONNECT): client sends CONNECT example.com:443 HTTP/1.1
//   -> proxy: resolve DNS, tcp_connect(example.com:443)
//   -> send 200 Connection Established -> relay_bidirectional(client_fd, target_fd)
// SOCKS5: client -> socks5_handshake -> auth -> socks5_request(CONNECT, host, port)
//   -> proxy: connect to target -> socks5_reply(success, bound_addr) -> relay
// reverse proxy: client -> proxy -> backend_select -> forward request
//   -> add x_forwarded_for + x_forwarded_proto -> upstream response -> return to client

// This defines HTTP CONNECT tunneling, SOCKS5/4a proxying, reverse proxy
// with sticky sessions, header rewriting, and SSL termination/passthrough.

