// Semantic direction:
// middleware wraps an http_handler to add cross-cutting behavior before or after the core logic.
// middleware_chain applies middleware_fns in order; each calls next_handler to pass control forward.
// request_ctx carries request-scoped values (request ID, user, trace) through the middleware chain.
// router matches incoming request_targets against route_patterns and dispatches to registered handlers.
// route_params extracts named segments from the URL path (e.g. /users/:id → params.id).
// route_wildcard matches any suffix after a fixed prefix (e.g. /static/*).
// logging_middleware writes an access_log entry with method, path, status, and latency for every request.
// log_request_id attaches a unique request identifier to every log entry for correlation.
// auth_middleware validates credentials (Bearer token, session cookie) before the handler runs.
// rate_limit_middleware enforces request quotas; it integrates with the token_bucket (z328).
// cors_middleware adds Access-Control headers and handles preflight OPTIONS requests.
// compress_middleware applies gzip or brotli if the client sends a matching accept_encoding header.
// compress_threshold skips compression for small responses where overhead exceeds savings.
// timeout_middleware wraps each request in a context_deadline_mw; the handler is cancelled on expiry.
// recover_middleware catches panics from downstream handlers and returns a 500 response.
// body_read_limit prevents large uploads from exhausting memory by capping body bytes read.
// x_request_id is the standard header for propagating request IDs across service boundaries.
// etag_static enables conditional GET for static files; 304 Not Modified avoids retransmitting unchanged files.
// cache_control_static sets long expiry for fingerprinted assets and short expiry for HTML.
// template_handler renders an HTML template with template_data and writes the result as the response body.

// Primitive flow:
// request arrives -> middleware_chain:
//   recover_middleware (wrap all)
//   -> tracing_middleware (start span)
//   -> logging_middleware (record start time)
//   -> auth_middleware (validate token -> 401 if invalid)
//   -> rate_limit_middleware (check quota -> 429 if exceeded)
//   -> cors_middleware (add headers or handle preflight)
//   -> timeout_middleware (context with deadline)
//   -> compress_middleware (wrap response writer)
//   -> router (match route -> extract params -> handler_fn)
//   -> handler response
//   logging_middleware records status + latency
//   tracing_middleware ends span
// recover: handler panics -> recover_middleware catches -> 500 + stack_trace_resp (dev only)

// This defines the HTTP middleware chain, router with named parameters,
// access logging, auth, rate limiting, CORS, compression, timeouts, and static file serving.

