// Semantic direction:
// canvas is the drawing surface backed by a GPU or software renderer.
// canvas_scale handles high-DPI displays: scale 2.0 doubles the pixel density.
// backend_wgpu is the cross-platform GPU backend using the WebGPU API.
// draw_begin and draw_end bracket one frame; draw_flush submits GPU commands.
// draw_clear fills the entire canvas with clear_color before the frame's content.
// paint describes how a shape is filled: solid color, gradient, or tiled pattern.
// paint_blend_mode controls how new pixels combine with existing pixels.
// blend_multiply darkens by multiplying channel values; blend_screen lightens.
// color_premultiply converts an RGBA color to premultiplied alpha for correct blending.
// color_lerp interpolates between two colors by a factor for smooth transitions.
// stroke defines how outlines are drawn: width, cap style, join style, and dash pattern.
// cap_round_s rounds the ends of open strokes; join_miter extends corners to a sharp point.
// dash_pattern alternates drawn and skipped lengths along the stroke.
// path is a sequence of drawing commands; path_fill renders the enclosed area; path_stroke outlines it.
// path_curve_to draws a cubic Bezier curve using two control points.
// path_arc draws a circular arc by center, radius, start angle, and end angle.
// push_transform saves the current coordinate transform; pop_transform restores it.
// transform_matrix applies an arbitrary 2D affine transformation.
// clip_rect limits drawing to a rectangular region; clip_path clips to an arbitrary path.
// text_baseline controls vertical alignment of text relative to the draw position.
// draw_image places a raster image at image_rect with configurable scale_mode.
// shadow renders a drop shadow under the next drawn shape; shadow_blur controls softness.

// Primitive flow:
// frame: draw_begin(canvas) -> draw_clear(bg_color)
//   for each widget in paint_order:
//     push_transform(widget.bounds.origin)
//     push_clip(widget.bounds.size)
//     render_background(paint_color)
//     render_border(stroke_width, stroke_color)
//     draw_text(content, font, paint_color)
//     pop_clip -> pop_transform
//   draw_end -> submit to GPU -> swap buffers -> displayed

// This defines the drawing and rendering pipeline: canvas backends, paint,
// color, stroke, path, transforms, clipping, text rendering, and image drawing.

