// Semantic direction:
// terminal is the text-mode I/O interface; term_fd is the file descriptor for the controlling terminal.
// ansi_escape sequences are byte strings that control cursor, color, and screen state.
// escape_prefix is ESC (0x1B); csi is ESC[ (Control Sequence Introducer) for most cursor/color commands.
// cursor_goto moves the cursor to an absolute row and column (1-based).
// cursor_save stores the current cursor position; cursor_restore returns to it.
// cursor_hide prevents the cursor from flickering during rapid screen updates.
// cursor_style_bar draws a thin vertical bar cursor; useful in text editors.
// erase_line_right clears from the cursor to the end of the current line without moving it.
// erase_screen_down clears from the cursor to the bottom of the screen.
// alternate_screen is a secondary screen buffer; enter_alt_screen switches to it, exit_alt_screen returns.
// Full-screen TUI apps use the alternate_screen so the terminal history is preserved on exit.
// scroll_region_set limits scrolling to a defined row range; useful for pinning headers and footers.
// hyperlink uses OSC 8 to embed clickable URLs in terminal text.
// terminal_size returns the current term_cols and term_rows; sigwinch fires on resize.
// on_resize registers a callback that receives the new size when the terminal window is resized.
// set_title updates the terminal window title bar.
// push_title and pop_title save and restore the title, useful for nested TUI apps.

// Primitive flow:
// TUI startup: enter_alt_screen -> cursor_hide -> query_size -> render initial frame
// move to row 5, col 10: cursor_goto(5, 10) -> write(CSI "5;10H")
// clear line: cursor_goto(row, 1) -> erase_line -> write content
// resize: SIGWINCH signal -> on_resize callback -> query_size -> re-render all widgets
// TUI shutdown: cursor_show -> exit_alt_screen -> erase_screen -> cursor_goto(1,1)
// hyperlink: osc8_open(url) -> write text -> osc8_close -> terminal renders as clickable link

// This defines terminal I/O primitives: ANSI escape sequences, cursor control,
// screen erasing, alternate screen, scroll regions, size detection, and hyperlinks.

