// Semantic direction:
// tui_widget is the base trait: every widget knows its area and can render to a buffer.
// widget_area is the terminal rectangle allocated to this widget during layout.
// cell is one terminal character position: a Unicode character with fg/bg colors and style.
// cell_skip marks a cell as continuation of a wide (full-width) character to the left.
// buffer holds the full screen's cells; buffer_diff computes only the changed cells to minimize writes.
// buffer_merge applies one buffer on top of another, used for layered rendering.
// block_widget draws a titled border around any content; border_rounded uses ╭╮╰╯ corners.
// block_title is rendered in the top border; block_padding adds inner spacing.
// text_widget renders styled text with alignment and overflow handling.
// overflow_ellipsis truncates text and appends "…" when it exceeds the available width.
// para_scroll_t allows large text blocks to be scrolled within a fixed area.
// list_state tracks the selected item and scroll offset; list_next/prev move the selection.
// list_highlight_style is applied to the selected item for visual feedback.
// table_widths specifies the column sizing: fixed, percentage, or minimum constraints.
// gauge_widget renders a horizontal progress bar filling gauge_value / gauge_max of the width.
// sparkline_widget shows a compact bar chart of recent sparkline_data values.
// chart_widget renders bar or line charts within a terminal area.
// axis_bounds set the data range displayed on each axis; axis_labels annotate tick marks.
// canvas_tui provides a low-level drawing surface using Unicode braille patterns for sub-cell resolution.
// canvas_braille maps 2×4 dot patterns to Braille Unicode code points for smooth curves and lines.

// Primitive flow:
// render cycle: layout -> each widget.render_tui(buffer, area)
//   block_widget: draw border chars at edges, render title in top border
//   list_widget: for each visible item: render text_widget(item, area_row)
//     selected_item: apply list_highlight_style
//   table_widget: render header row, then data rows with column widths
//   buffer_diff(prev_buffer, curr_buffer) -> only changed cells -> write to terminal
// input: list_widget.handle_event_tui(key_down) -> list_next -> re-render

// This defines the TUI widget system: cell buffer, block borders, text, lists,
// tables, gauges, sparklines, charts, and braille canvas drawing.

