// Semantic direction:
// term_color represents a terminal color in one of three formats: basic 16, 256-palette, or RGB.
// color_bright_black is typically rendered as dark gray; it and its siblings are the bright ANSI colors.
// color_256_index selects one of the 256 xterm palette entries.
// color_256_from_rgb finds the nearest xterm-256 palette color for a given RGB value.
// color_rgb_t carries three 0–255 byte values; rgb_to_ansi_fg emits ESC[38;2;r;g;bm.
// style_tui bundles a foreground color, background color, and a set of modifiers.
// style_bold emits SGR 1; style_dim emits SGR 2 for reduced brightness.
// style_undercurl draws a wavy underline (supported in Kitty, WezTerm, and iTerm2).
// style_undercolor sets the underline color independently of the text color.
// style_patch merges two styles: the second style's non-default values override the first.
// styled_text is a tree of span_t values; each span has a content string and a style_tui.
// line_t is one line of spans; text_t is multiple lines used by multi-line widgets.
// encode_fg_rgb emits the 24-bit color escape; encode_fg_256 emits the 256-palette escape.
// encode_reset emits ESC[0m to clear all active styles.
// tui_theme bundles named styles for consistent visual treatment across a TUI application.
// theme_selected_style is used for highlighted list items; theme_border_style colors widget borders.
// theme_nord uses the Nord color palette (blue-grey backgrounds, icy blues and greens).
// style_add_modifier adds one modifier flag; style_remove_modifier clears it without touching others.

// Primitive flow:
// render cell: style_fg=rgb(220,50,50), style_bold=true
//   -> encode_fg_rgb(220,50,50) -> ESC[38;2;220;50;50m
//   -> encode_modifiers(bold) -> ESC[1m
//   -> write char -> encode_reset -> ESC[0m
// theme application: widget.style = theme.normal_style (fg=theme.fg, bg=theme.bg)
//   selected item: widget.style = theme.selected_style (fg=theme.accent, bg=theme.selection_bg)
// 256-color fallback: has_truecolor? -> rgb else color_256_from_rgb(r,g,b)

// This defines terminal color modes (basic/256/RGB), style modifiers,
// styled text spans, ANSI encoding, and named TUI themes.

