}

// Semantic direction:
// streaming_replication sends WAL records from primary_db to standby_db in real time.
// walsender runs on primary; walreceiver runs on standby; they communicate over replication_protocol.
// replication_slot guarantees the primary retains WAL until the standby has consumed it.
// slot_catalog_xmin prevents the primary from vacuuming rows the standby still needs.
// replication_lag is the difference between primary flush_lsn and standby apply_lsn.
// synchronous_replication waits for at least one sync_standby to confirm receipt before committing.
// quorum_commit requires any_sync (any N of M) standbys to acknowledge before commit.
// logical_replication decodes WAL changes into row-level events for selective replication.
// publication declares which tables to replicate and which operations (insert/update/delete).
// subscription connects to a publication and applies decoded change_events to local tables.
// logical_slot retains WAL for logical decoding; a downstream subscriber consumes the slot.
// base_backup is a consistent snapshot of the data directory; backup_start_lsn marks where WAL replay begins.
// backup_manifest lists all backup files with checksums for verification on restore.
// pitr (Point-In-Time Recovery) replays WAL from a base_backup up to a restore_target.
// target_time recovers to a wall-clock timestamp; target_lsn_restore to an exact WAL position.
// restore_wal fetches archived WAL segments via restore_command (from archiving in z389).
// reach_target fires when the specified recovery_target is passed during WAL replay.
// promote transitions a standby to become the new primary after failover.
// timeline_switch records that the new primary diverged from the old at a given LSN.
// reattach_standby connects old standbys to the new primary using timeline_history.

// Primitive flow:
// streaming: standby -> start_replication(slot, lsn) -> primary walsender: send_wal stream
//   standby: receive_wal -> apply_wal -> apply_lsn update
//   standby: replication_feedback(standby_lsn, flush_lsn, apply_lsn) -> primary tracks lag
// synchronous: commit -> wait_for_sync(first_sync) -> standby confirms flush_lsn -> proceed
// PITR: take base_backup -> run workload -> crash
//   restore: base_backup restored -> recovery_conf(target_time="2026-05-28 14:30")
//   -> start DB: restore_wal(archives) -> apply WAL until reach_target -> promote
// logical: CREATE PUBLICATION p FOR TABLE users; CREATE SUBSCRIPTION s CONNECTION '...' PUBLICATION p;
//   -> change_events decoded and applied to subscriber

// This defines streaming and logical replication, synchronous commit,
// replication slots, base backup, PITR with archived WAL, and failover promotion.

