// Semantic direction:
// vm_core is the execution engine that fetches and dispatches bytecode instructions.
// call_frame holds the execution context for one active function call.
// frame_ip is the instruction pointer within the current function's code.
// frame_stack_base is the index in value_stack where this frame's locals begin.
// frame_catch_ip is the exception landing pad; 0 means no active try block.
// frame_prev links to the caller's frame for return and stack unwinding.
// call_stack is the chain of frames; stack_push_frame adds one; stack_pop_frame removes it.
// stack_overflow fires when stack_depth exceeds max_call_depth.
// value_stack is the operand stack shared across all frames; each frame has its own window.
// vstack_slot accesses a value at an absolute stack index (used for local variables).
// value is a tagged union; val_type is the runtime type tag.
// val_upvalue_ref holds a reference to an upvalue, which may be open (on stack) or closed (heap).
// function_obj is the compiled function prototype: code, constants, and metadata.
// func_upvalue_descriptors describe whether each upvalue is from the enclosing stack or its upvalues.
// closure_obj wraps a function_obj with its captured upvalues.
// upvalue starts open (pointing to a stack slot in the enclosing frame) and is closed when that frame exits.
// close_upvalues copies open upvalues that are about to go out of scope to the heap.
// constant_pool holds literals embedded in the function: integers, floats, strings, nested functions.
// stack_trace walks the call_stack and collects frame_info for error reporting.

// Primitive flow:
// vm_run: loop: fetch instr at frame_ip -> ip_advance -> vm_dispatch
//   op_call: save current frame -> stack_push_frame(new_frame) -> continue
//   op_return_val: pop result, stack_pop_frame -> push result to caller's stack
// closure creation: op_build_closure -> walk func_upvalue_descriptors
//   -> if from enclosing stack: create open upvalue pointing to slot
//   -> if from enclosing upvalues: share the existing upvalue
// frame exit: close_upvalues(frame_stack_base) -> all open upvalues in this frame closed
// stack trace: walk frame_prev chain -> collect trace_func_name + trace_line_number per frame

// This defines the stack-based VM core: call frames, value stack,
// closures with upvalues, constant pools, and stack traces.

