// Semantic direction:
// green_thread is a lightweight cooperative thread managed entirely in user space.
// Each green_thread has its own stack_g, register_set, and thread_id_g.
// stack_guard_g is a protected page at the bottom of the stack to detect overflow.
// grow_stack doubles the stack when it overflows (segfault on guard page → allocate larger stack).
// scheduler_g maintains a run_queue of runnable threads and a blocked_queue for waiting ones.
// yield_g suspends the current thread and places it at the back of run_queue.
// context_switch saves the current register_set (sp, ip, fp, callee-saved regs) and restores another.
// spawn_g creates a new green_thread with its own stack; it enters run_queue immediately.
// join_g blocks the calling thread until thread_handle completes and thread_result is available.
// work_steal_g balances load: when a local_sched's run_queue is empty, steal_batch threads from a steal_victim.
// park_thread suspends a thread without putting it on run_queue; unpark_thread re-enables it.
// park_condition is a predicate checked before unparking to avoid spurious wake-ups.
// thread_local_g provides per-thread storage not shared across threads.
// tl_get and tl_set read and write a tl_value keyed by tl_key for the current thread.
// preempt_g is a cooperative preemption point inserted at backward branches and function entries.

// Primitive flow:
// spawn_g(fn, args): alloc stack_g -> save fn+args -> create green_thread -> enqueue
// schedule_next: run_queue.dequeue -> context_switch(current, next)
// yield: current -> run_queue.enqueue -> schedule_next
// join: if thread_handle not done: park_thread(current) -> schedule_next
//   on thread exit: unpark_thread(joiner)
// work stealing: local run_queue empty -> pick steal_victim -> steal_half of their queue

// This defines green threads: cooperative scheduling, context switching,
// stack management, work stealing, and thread-local storage.

