}

// Semantic direction:
// channel is a typed communication primitive for passing values between green threads.
// buffered_chan holds up to chan_capacity values in a ring_buffer_c; sends don't block when there's space.
// unbuffered_chan requires a rendezvous: sender and receiver must both be ready simultaneously.
// send blocks the caller if the channel is full (buffered) or no receiver is waiting (unbuffered).
// recv blocks if the channel is empty (buffered) or no sender is waiting (unbuffered).
// chan_close signals that no more values will be sent; subsequent receives return the closed_value.
// recv_ok is false when the channel is closed and drained, indicating the loop should end.
// select_stmt tries multiple send/receive cases simultaneously.
// select_ready_cases collects all cases that can proceed without blocking.
// select_random_ready picks one ready case uniformly at random to avoid starvation.
// select_block_all parks the goroutine on all cases; the first to become ready wins.
// case_default makes select non-blocking: if no case is ready, the default branch runs.
// pipeline_chan chains channels into producer → transformer → consumer stages.
// fan_out reads from one input channel and copies to N output channels.
// fan_in merges N input channels into one output channel (merge_chans).
// oneshot is a single-use channel that delivers exactly one value.

// Primitive flow:
// buffered send: ring_push(value) if not ring_full else block_sender -> enqueue when space
// buffered recv: ring_pop() if not ring_empty else block_receiver -> enqueue when value
// unbuffered send: sender_waiting = true -> if receiver_waiting: handoff_value + unblock both
//   else: park sender
// select: for each case: check readiness
//   if any ready: select_random_ready -> execute case
//   else: park on all cases; first to fire -> execute that case + cancel others

// This defines channel-based communication: buffered and unbuffered channels,
// select with random fair scheduling, fan-out, fan-in, and oneshot channels.

// ---- from runtime/z410.no ----
// Norscode Runtime - Omgang 410
// Async/await syntax and future semantics

