// Semantic direction:
// verden is the ECS container: it holds all entities, components, archetypes, and systems.
// entitet is a lightweight identifier: a numeric id paired with a generasjon counter.
// entitet_generasjon prevents stale references: after deletion, the same id has a new generation.
// komponent is a plain data type attached to entities (no behavior, only data).
// arketype groups entities that have the same set of component types together in contiguous memory.
// ark_kolonne is one component array within an archetype; all columns have the same length.
// Moving an entity to a different archetype when components are added/removed is ark_flytt_entitet.
// spørring specifies which components to include (med) and exclude (uten).
// spørring_kjør iterates all entities matching the query; spørring_endre_ecs gives mutable access.
// system is a function that operates on a spørring; systems are registered in the planlegger.
// planlegger_fase organizes systems into ordered phases: pre-update, update, post-update, draw.
// system_parallell_ecs allows two systems to run concurrently if their queries don't conflict.
// ressurs_ecs stores global singleton data (input state, time, renderer) accessible from any system.
// hendelse_ecs is a typed message bus; systems can send and receive events without direct coupling.
// stilling, hastighet, rotasjon, skala_ecs, and synlig_ecs are built-in transform components.
// merkelapp is a tag component (zero-size) used as a filter in queries.

// Primitive flow:
// verden_ny() → empty arketyper and spørring cache
// entitet_opprett() → assign id + generation → add to verden
// komponent_legg_til(entitet, Stilling{x:0, y:0}): find/create arketype(Stilling) → add entity
// spørring_bygg().med(Stilling).med(Hastighet).kjør() → iterate matching arketyper
//   → for each entitet: access stilling, hastighet components in contiguous memory
// planlegger_kjør: for each fase: for each system in fase:
//   run system function with its spørring results (in parallel if safe)

// This defines an ECS architecture: archetype-based storage, queries with
// include/exclude filters, a phased scheduler with parallel system execution.

